# Git Workflow for srt-slurm

## Golden Rule: Never push directly to origin

- `origin` (ishandhanani/srt-slurm) is the upstream repo. Do NOT push directly to it.
- Always push to `fork` (weireweire/srt-slurm) and file a PR.

## Remotes

- `origin`: https://github.com/ishandhanani/srt-slurm.git (upstream, read-only)
- `fork`: git@github.com:weireweire/srt-slurm.git (user's fork, push here)

## Branching

- When the user asks to "switch to" a branch, check if it exists on remote first (`git fetch origin <branch>` or `git fetch fork <branch>`) before creating a new one.
- If the branch already exists remotely, track it: `git checkout -b <branch> <remote>/<branch>`
- If you accidentally created a local branch without tracking, use `git reset --hard <remote>/<branch>` and `git branch -u <remote>/<branch>` to fix it.

## Committing

- Only commit when explicitly asked by the user.
- "提交" (submit) in context of recipes/configs likely means submitting a SLURM job (`srtctl apply`), NOT a git commit. Ask for clarification if ambiguous.
- When the user says "提交任务" or "提交测试", they mean submitting a SLURM job.
- When the user says "提交代码" or "commit", they mean a git commit.

## Pushing

- Push to `fork`, not `origin`:
  ```bash
  git push fork <branch-name>
  ```

## Creating PRs with gh

- Since `origin` is upstream (ishandhanani) and `fork` is user's repo, specify repo explicitly:
  ```bash
  gh pr create --repo ishandhanani/srt-slurm --head weireweire:<branch-name>
  ```
- Without `--head`, gh may fail or create the PR from the wrong fork.
- Without `--repo`, gh defaults to origin which is correct, but always double-check the target.

## Undoing Mistakes

- If you accidentally pushed to origin, coordinate with the user to revert.
- Use `git reset --hard <commit>` + `git push --force` only with explicit user confirmation.
- Always confirm before any destructive git operation (force push, reset --hard, branch delete).
